{"/service/ndnp/uuml/batch_uuml_hincapie_ver01/data/sn85058396/print/1914020901/0377.xml":{"full_text":"4 THE OCDEN STANDARD. OGDEN, UTAH. MONDAY, FEBRUARY 9, 1 91 4\nI gibe jtodawl\nWilliam Glasmaan, Publisher.\nAN INDEPENDENT NEWSPAPER.\n(Established 1S70\nThis paper will always flpht for\nprogress and reform. It will not know\ningly tolerate Injustice or corruption\nand will always fight demagogues oj\nall parties; it will oppose privileged\nclasses ancf public plunderer) it will\nnever lack sympathy with the poor;\nit will always remain devoted to the\npublic welfare and will never be sat\nisfied with merely printing news; it\nwill always be drastically independ\nent and will never be afraid to attack\nwroQR, whether committed by tho\nrich or the poor.\nI CHAIRMAN OF EXECUTIVE\nCOMMITTEE.\nIn the election of Judge If. II Ro\nlapp as chairman of the executive\ncommittee of the United States Beet\nSugar Industry, Ogdeit becomes the\nheadquarters of an organization\nwhich has in Its keeping the welfare\nof an industry extending all over the\ncountry, representing an investment\nof millions of dollars.\nThis is a distinct honor conferred\non Judge Rolapp. which his friends\nappreciate, and It is one more country-wide\nrecognition of Ogden.\nI N EXPERT FOR THE\nOGDEN SCHOOLS\nThe bureau of education Is a\nbranch of the government devoted to\na study of school problems, in the\nemploy of which are many expert\nschool men Why not invite one of\nthose experts to visit Ogden and go\nover our school system and point out\nIn a friendly way the needs of our\ninstitutions of learning0\nOne question that might be direct\ned at n trained investigator Is, Are\nour grade schools efficient0 If not,\nwhy?\nFor the purpose of restoring con\ntld ace, wo suggest that the nation\nal bureau of education be requested\nto inquire Into our school system, ei\nther to reassure us or point out what\never defects may exist.\nIt occurs to us that this plan might\nbe carried out in all the schools of\nUtah, to the benefit of the state's\neducational institutions.\nrr\nI THREE QUESTIONS BY AN\nOGDEN ATTORNEY.\nOne of our lawyers, a student of\neconomics, and well posted on public\naffairs generally, has suggested three\nquestion to be put to the eastern rail\nrouds now seeking a 5 per cent in\ncrease In freight rates. He says:\n\"Ask them whose fault it was that,\nthe railroads have not the money\nthey want for their eastern line.\n\"Ask them about the New Haven\n\"Ask them about the St. Louis\nFrisco.\n\"Is that the fault of the people, or\nbusiness conditions, or the Interstate\ncommerce commission?\"\nThe New Haven road was wrecked\nby speculation and fraud\nThe \"Frisco bankruptcy came from\nstock gambling. The Rock Island and\nOrient met disaster in the same way.\nAs a writer says, the people are tired\nof tho buccaneer method of running\nrailroads. That is the meaning of\nnil this. It does not mean dull times,\nor non-compensatory rates or any?\nthing else except that the public has\ndecided that railroads should bo run\nprimarily as public carriers and not\nas high finance and stock gambling\nenterprises.\nOf course, this is not a complete\nanswer to the demand for higher\nrates. If railroads run on business\nprinciples are suffering financial\nstringency because rates are too low,\nand, If such roads cannot buy neces\nsary equipment and make required\nextensions owing to lack of funds.\nthen there should be a granting of\ntheir demands for higher compensa\ntion for services to be performed. But\nthe evidence should bo conclusive\nand not baaed entirely on tho state\nments of over-zealous special plead\ncrs.\nAnd the increase should not be all\nembracing, unless it can be shown\nthat rates in all parts of the country\nare comparatively equitable. For in\nstance, the west should not be\ncalled on to submit to a five per\ncent increase, if it can be proved\nthat at present this division of\nthe country is suffering discrimi\nnation and is carrying more than Its\nproportionate share of the cost of\nmaintaining the railroads\nfS\nWOOL BUYERS IN\nTHE FIELD,\nThe New York Commercial says\nthis year's wool clips are already be\ning contracted for, and an option on\nmore than 1,000,000 pounds on south\nern Utah wools has been obtained.\nUnder Boston date, the New York\nI newspaper says: \"It is a question\nwhether the rush to contract for the\nnew domestic clip Is a Judicious pol\nicy, especially in view of the fact\nthat prices approximate those glveu\nfor tho wools a year ago\nAccording to this same article, the\nbuyers in Utah tried to work the\nflockmasters by only offering 11\ncents, but, falling to get any bites\nat this figure. It was soon advanced\nto 14, and one big 6ale was final 'y\nmade at 16 cents.\nA .Montana paper says there can\nbe no question that the firms send\ning out these buyers know what they\nare doing, and it Is evident that tfcey\naro trying to pick up all the wool\nthey can get at as low a price and\nas early as possible It may be\nthat these eastern gentlemen have\nmade up their minds that there will\nbe some pure fabric legislation at\nthis session of congress, which they\nrealize would materially increase the\ndemand for wool, and, consequently\nthe price of that article. Something\nIs in the wind or the buyers would\nnot be getting out so unusually early\nto make their contracts.\noo\nFOREIGNERS BY THE\nMILLIONS\nDescribing the rush of foreigners\nto the shores of America, Howe's\nMonthly says that In the last ten\nyears 9.370,000 Immigrants have been\nadmitted to the United States, of\nwhich more than 8,000,000 came\nthrough the port of New York. Near\nly 30,000 people arrive each day, or a\nnumber about equal to the popula\ntion of Ogden.\nEvery ten days there must be cre\nated in the United States a city the\nsize of Ogden to house and care for\nthe strangers. What a tremendous\ntask and yet how quietly the work\nproceeds! The great stream that\npours in through the gates at Ellis\nIsland, New York, flows in every di\nrection throughout the country, un\ntil it disappears in rivulets.\nIf an attempt were made to care\nfor the foreigners collectively, in\nstead of allowing each individual to\ngo his way. What a task it would\nimpose! The government collects a\nhead tax of $4 from each immigrant,\nand this fund has accumulated until\nthere is now a surplus of eight mil\nlion dollars. The immigrants arriv\ning at the port of New York are tak\nen to Ellis Island, where the govern\nment maintains a great establish\nment for their accommodation. Cer\ntain persons aro excluded as immi\ngrants; the feeble-minded, the phys\nically unfit, criminals, etc, and oth\ners who may become a charge on the\ngovernment, or harm it in various\nways. Immigranti are fed while be\ning held for Inspection, and the food\nis fairly good, but the sleeping quar-\nH IF YOUR H\nI -'Two is company-Three is a crowd\"\nJ! I fit yr feet with the aid of the foot.o-graph and I\nm I I your toes will never be crowded\n-Every day 25,000 people walk into Walk-Over stores!\nI 1 \"!Zn9 f ,many, f th6m kw for the first tim thel\nfj.; I meaning of absolute foot comfort. I\nI -Arch Supports--\"Foot-Easers\"\n:tl ll0 yOUr fnet ache?eet( oh, so tired! Do you run your\nI 'I I Bho6f Pver? Better call and have our expert fit you with\ni I Pjk. Properly adjusted to YOUR feet. They cure fallen\nj I arches and help weak ankles.\n0i !j SEE OUR WINDOWS.\nM I Walk-Overs for Men and Women $3.50 Upwards.\nI I WALK-OVER BOOT SHOP\nVm j 2470 Washington Avenue. W. K. FleUchmann, Manager.\nI\ntors are bad. First cabin passengers\nin arriving ships are not bothered\nmuch, except by customs inspectors,\nbut thero is a stricter examination of\nsecond clasB passengers, and a very\nstrict one of immigrants. Tho bulk\nof the arriving immigrants nre of\nstrong peasant stock, and have but\nllttlo trouble in passing the inspec\ntors. Many of them are recruited in\nforeign countries by agents of the\nsteamship companies, who visit vll\nI lagpR, and tell the people of fortunes\nto be made in prosperous America\nThe business of bringing immigrants\nto this country, even at the low rates,\nis very profitable, and ship managers\nfrequently quarrel over It, and cut\nrates.\nSome days the arriving Immigrants\nat. Ellis island number more than five\nthousand. In case an immigrant is\nrefused admission to the country for\nany reason, the steamship company\nbringing him over Is compelled to\ntake him back. Immigrants are close\nly Inspected by the steamship offi\ncials before they aro accepted as\npassengers, as they are always con\nfronted with the possible necrsstn\nof earning them back, and foodlns\nthem during the voyage. Porraerly\na great many Germans, English and\nIrish, came to the United States, but\nnow the immigrants mainly come\nfrom Austria, Hungary' and Italy.\noo\nEXPANSION NOTED IN\nBUSINESS.\nIJradstreet's continues to record the\nreturn of prosperity. The report for\nlast week, summarizing trade events,\naid:\n\"Optimism continues to spread and j\nIn some lines of Industry, particularly I\niron and steel, actual Improvement\nkeeps encouraging pace with sent!\nment. Withal there Is sufficient ir\nregularity, primarily traceable to un\nseasonable weather conditions, to act\nns a check in the general tendency\ntoward betterment.\n\"In the forefront is the fact that\ntrade with the larger distributors is\ne.ianding and for so early in tho\nseason it may be deemed to be en\ncouragingly good, while movements\non the whole surpass those of this\ntime last year. Buyers are In the\nleading markets and while reports of\nsome lines have devoted the week\nmostly to inspecting displays, gradu\nally improvement is the order of the\nday.\"\nThe National Copper bank letter of\nlast Saturday discloses the fact that\nthe intermountain country is enjoy\ning its full share of the Improving\nconditions. It tells of expnnding\nrailroads, of greater electric power\nlines, of increasing mine activities,\nof great agricultural development,\nand, referring to Idaho, says.\n\"Idaho can now claim to be one or\nthe most Important wheat 6tates.\nGreat progress has been made, espe\ncially in the region around American\nFalls, Idaho, which is said to stand\ntoday as the second wheat-shipping\npoint In the United States, whereas\neven so short a time as five years\nago its wheat shipments were negli\nglble in quantity.'\"\nAs Idaho is tributary to Ogden's\nwholesale district, the prosperity of\nthat state can be fairly claimed as\na part of our own bright outlook.\noo\nROCK ISLAND AGAIN\nUNSETTLES MARKET\nNew York, Feb. 9. The stock mar\nket was again unsettled soon after\nthe strong opening today by reason\nof further weakness in the Rock Isl\nand securities, all of which fell to\nlower records. Dealings In Rock Isl\nand common and preferred, as well\nas in Chicago, Rock Island Pacific\ncollateral trust 4 per cent bonds were\nfairly extensive, and suggested liquid\natlon on the part of holders.\nThere was recurrent weakness in\nNew Haven and New York Central,\nas a result of week-end developments\nwhich Indicated further federal In\nquiry Into those properties.\nOn the curb the oil shares were\nalso very weak. Atlantic Refining,\na Standard Oil subsidiary, fell from\n820, last Saturday's closing price, to\n743 In the first hour's trading.\nUIJ\nUNCLE OF SCHUYLER COLFAX\nDEAD\nHartford. Conn.. Feb 9. James\nMandevllle. a well known contractor\nand an uncle of Schuyler Colfax, vice\npresident of the United States during\nPresident Grant's first term, died j\nhere today, aged 99.\nru-\nJOSEPH HOWELL ON\nSTORMBOUND TRAIN\nHancock, Mich Feb. 9. The train\nbearing Representative Joseph How\nell of Utah the member necessary to\nmake a quorum of the congressional\nInvestigating committee, was report\ned stormbound somewhere on the\nlower penknsula this morning and\nprospects for a meeting dwindled as\nthe day advanced.\nChairman Taylor declared that it\nwas unlikely that hearings would be\ngin before tomorrow.\noo\nCOPPER STATEMENT SHOWS\nA LARGE DECREASE\nNew York. Feb. 9 Tho statement\nof the Topper Producers' association\nof February 1, shows a decrease In\nstocks on hand of 4.142,182 pounds\noo\nRAKER TO URGE BILL\nWashington. Feb. 9. Representa\ntive Raker. Democrat of California,\ntoday announced his purpose to call\nup his bill Tor Asiatic exclusion at\nThursday s meeting of tho immigra\ntion committee, despito the dlsposl-\nI tion to defer to Secretary Bryan's re-\nquest to postpone.\nWomen's and Misses'\nCoats and Suits\nStill Further Reduced y\nTo effect a decisive disposal of Women's and Misses' Garments, we offer this week\nthe most remarkable reductions of the season. Note the great price concessions: ft\n\"\"r fyf 125 $20 to $25 Ladies' and Misses\" Fall and\nCorset Sale mm I tu j\n75c Corsets 59 3 7v ta tV Jjfl Wk J8 JH\n$5.00 Front Lace Cor- MS. fT$k THF W M ah\n3ets--\"-92.50 f L I L I I 2S\n$3 00 Front Lace Cor- i kr W T ovni\nsets 1.50 I wmmjn I\n$10rn0rJ,rOnt Mn ifiMP 120-$12 to $15 Ladies' and Misses' Cloth CI\nCorsets.. $7.50 ,ym$- n cM\n$8 50 Front Lace Modart W H Coats and Laracul Coats comp\nCorsets 5.75 ffl $it? iJi jm \"\"V ,u\n$6.50 Front Lace Modart ffi I JBi M A ffl B rordi\nCorsets $4.50 b-:'. i: f ffl B mkm Char\n$5.00 Front Lace Modart \"3 'kT VI\nCorsets $3.75 F X I to O\ni$7ziTl Worce3t3.5o lillll T\" J vJJ B\n$6.00 Royal Worcester ;:-'V-:jj'j d-a\nJ3'\"4 I--\"\"-9300 Wggffl 1 162-$20 to $35 Ladies' and Misses' Winter\n$4 00 Royal Worcester fc:''V.?.f r i r I Old\nCorsets $2.00 WWM Cloth Coats 25 ce.\n$360 Royal Worcester J Tk\n$3.00 Royal Worcester V feL M M T \"Hlgl\nCorsets S 1 .50 (T jffik fl\n$2.00 Royal Worcester jfA Vfk M M B elve-\ncorsets 91.00 W\nward\nIprecii\nLAST 8b THOMAS j!\nWITNESSES 10\nOFFERDEFEM\nTwo Officials and Two Em\nployes of Western Fuel Co.\non the Stand.\nSan Francisco. Feb. 0. Two offi\ncials and two employes of the West\nern Fuel company, on trial for de\nfrauding the government of customs\nrebates through false weights, pre\npared to take the stand here todav In\ntheir own defense. They are Jamea\nB. Smith, vice president and general\nmanager; F. C Mills, superintendent,\nEdward J. Smith, checker and E. H\nMayer, weigher.\nOverages in coal weights, whicb\nthey concede, amounted to 62,i)00 tons\nwere negligible, the four were pre\npared to testify, in comparison to the\nnmount of coal handled, amounting\nto between 2 and 3 per cent. While\nthey maintain that such a discrep\nancy Is immaterial anyway, they ex\nplain that the government weighs\ncoal on a rising beam basis while\nthe company weighs it on an evenly\nbalanced beam, and thi3 in itself,\nthey hold. Is enough to explain the\ndifference.\nSpecial stress will be placed upon\nthe fact that the government made\nno attempt to show any manipulation\nof scales.\nA. M Folsom, a professor at Staf\nford university was expected to com\nplete some technical testimony for\nthe defense, at the opening of court.\noo\nCHARLES G. GATES'\nWILL FOR PROBATE\nMinneapolis. Feb. 9. The heirs of\nthe late Charles G. Gates and the In\nheritance department of the Minne\nsota attorney-general's office hnv-\nreached an agreement whereby the\nGates will j8 to be admitted to pro\nbats In this state, according to a\nstatement by Attorney General L. A.\nSmith today The taxable property\nin this state, Mr Smith stated, is\n$2,250,000 and the tax to bo collect\ned by the state Is 582.538\noo\nMcCREERYABLETO\nMANAGE AFFAIRS\nSan Francisco, Fob. 9 Backed up\nby a favorable decision of an Eng\nlish court relative to his ability to\nlook after hi own affairs. Walter A.\nMcCreery, the millionaire clubman\nand polo player, appeared today In\nsuperior court for a hearing on his\napplication to be restored by the\nCalifornia courts to competency. H\nH. McPIke, the attorney who was\nnamed as McCreery'n guardian, and\nfrom whose custody on a ranch near\nHollister the millionaire escaped Oc\ntober 26, I9i3 was on hand to op-1\npose the petition for restoration. Mc\nCreery returned yesterday to San\nFrancisco.\nuu\nTODAY IN CONGRESS\nWashington, Feb. 9 The day In\ncongress\nSenate.\nMet at noon.\nConsideration of constitutional\namendment for woman suffrage de\nferred. Immigration committee continued\nwork in Burnett bill, containing a\nliteracy test.\nHouse.\nMet at noon\nGovernor Glynn and other NVw\nYork officials asked the foreign af\nfairs committee to permit Nets York\nto regulate the diversion of Niagara\nriver water for power.\nTrust hearings continued before\nvarious committees.\nRepresentative Raker announced\nhis Intention to push his Asiatic ex\nclusion bill.\nSTUDENTS HONOR HOUSTON\nAustin, Texas. Feb. 9. Two thou\ni sand students of the University of\nTexas met Secretary of Agriculture\nHouston and Secretary of the Ti i\nury McAdoo. when they arrived here\ntoday to hold a regional bank hearing-\nThe students' act was in the\nnature of a home-coming greeting to\nSecretary' Houston, who was former\nly president of the university.\noo\nSHORTEST RAILWAY\nIN THE WORLD\nOakland. Cal.. Feb. 9 What is\nsaid to be the shortest municipal\nstreet railway system in the world\nmeasuring 391 feet, the leriKth of a\ncity block was put Into operation\nhere yesterday. The line was built\nby the city to connect the two ends\nof a street car system and give cross\ntown service. It Is leased to the lo\ncal stroet car company at tho rate\nof ono dollar a foot a year.\nThe car company had refused to\nconstruct the line for the city bo\ncause its officials were unable to fig\nure approximately what the revenue\nwould amount to The city Is to re\nceive five per cent of tho earnings\nof the line.\n'SECRETARY WILSON\n1 JOINS LECTURERS\nWashington. Feb. 9. Secretary\nWilson of the department of lctbor.\nIs the lecture platform's latest ac\nquisition from the ranks of govern-\nment officials. With Gifford IMnchot\nbe will go over th.- -prinK circuit I\nthrough Pennsylvania. I'lnchot will j\nuphold the principles of the Progres- j\nslvo party in which he is a candniat.\nfor the senate; Secretary Wilson will\nuphold the cause of Democracy. I\nwhose senatorial nomination Repr\nMBatlTi Richard L Palmer is seek\ning. Despite the fact that the lec j\nlures of both will pertain to th. po\nlltical phases of the Pennsylvania I\ni\nsenate campaign, they will be paid affairs.\nBIG GREY WOLF\nIN CITVSTREET\nKansas City, Mo., Feb. 9 A large\nhair-starved, grey wolf, after biting\ntwo persons, frightening :i score oi\nothers and spreading consternation\nthrough a staid and fashionable South\nSide residence district, was shot and\nkilled on Linwood boulevard hen\ntoday\nThe wolf sprang upon Miss Ann.\nHarrison as she waited for a itreei\nwill\nfSSSSSSSSSS mmmm I who\nstate\ncar. Miss Harrison screamed, threw ltft\nher fur muff at the animal and while\nthe muff was being torn to shreds,\nscaped into a. house. Her clothing 001\ntrafl torn, but she was unhurt. Thn teanti\nwolf ran down the boulevard pursued 7\nby a milkman who hurled bottles as 'on\nhe ran. Two blocks from the scene See\nof the first attack, the wolf snapped Ball i\nat a negro domestic causing a pain- sco\nful wound In the arm. A number den 5\nOf grocery boys, business men and ser- Ham\nvants from boulevard homes. Joined lu Scotc\nthe chase. A riot call was sent into comp\npolice headquarters and an automo- booke\nbile with a hall' dozen patrolmen bur- n,OT\nried to the scene. gjj8\"\noo the\nInstead. pace(\n\"What a wretched picture!\" remark- of at\ned the visitor at the salon. \"I wonder DR. I\nhow they ever happened to hang it7\" ted\n\"Oh, the artist escaped probably.\" 406-40\nGirl\npounc\ngood\nI YOU WILL RECEIVE A CORDIAL W\nI WELCOME j S\n8 at the Commercial National Bank of Ogden. I Jfj\n1 and in every transaction the most courteous them.\nB and liberal treatment. \"weni\nif Our Facilities enable us to render a bank- ufi\ni'j m If\n5 Butter\nthis a\nS\"V: L\nI: m HOME JONGJflCRr:P JDNGJ-LOVE JQNGfjj S2\n1 1 Song Book Coupon 1 E\n2 PRESENTED BY THE S jj u'w\nj OGDEN STANDARD, Feb. 9. if j\nZ S AT EXPLAINED BELOW\nt IfeJ SEVEN SOAIG BOOKS IN OME jJ f B\nB COLLEGE JCNGJ\"-OPERATIC .nvr.rjg f 0\nfSIX OF THESE COUPONsf i\nEntitle the bearer to a choice ol cither 1\nX the beautiful song boohs described below l\nwhea ceompnuel by (be aspen amount ioiuuIi. k- ..it. 2 MM\nt CTer. th. item, of th. co.t op.li,n,. mMTSEXXtSS? J H\nA hira. and otW DecuMry nptu, itcmi 'ctory, chacki,,,, dark J M\nI \"SONGS THAT NEVER GROW OLD\" ILLUSTRATED I S\nf A grand collection of all the old favorite ,ones emml1\nwith the utmost care by the molt competent authors iluiriS I 55\nI a rare galaxy of 6o wonderful portrait o. the wSXS W,th\nman, -n f.or.te QOMOMM. Th.. big Sok contt.n, n.. nl H grCat?! VOCal arUstS, I Jatt\nC to, the besnUfnl heavy MZuSZ I!\nim eontsnU In pnper binding. 69 eentVnec tr I ma\" 1\nj","height":"28020","width":"20898"}}
